  <notes>
    The scheduler topology choice (task 001) determines WHERE messages come from (Logic Apps timer publishing to SB, native SB scheduled message, etc.) but NOT the handler shape. The handler is invariant — it consumes a `ScheduledActionDispatchJob` regardless of which scheduler enqueued it. If the runtime ADR chose a path that bypasses Service Bus, this task is moot — flag the conflict in `notes/handoffs/`.

    Do NOT inject `IActionOrchestrationService` (task 041 internal) directly. Go through `IActionEngineFacade` (task 015). The handler is "CRUD-side" from the orchestrator's view — same G12 boundary as the endpoint layer (task 040).

    The deterministic `IdempotencyKey` uses ScheduledForUtc to the minute (`yyyyMMddHHmm`) — this prevents duplicates from at-least-once redelivery within the same scheduled tick. If the scheduler fires twice at slightly different sub-minute timestamps (which it shouldn't), the key collapses to the same value and the second message is no-op'd via `IIdempotencyService`.

    Cancellation handling: a job that's cancelled mid-execution returns `JobOutcome.Succeeded` per ADR-017 — cancellation is a clean exit, not a failure. The orchestrator (task 041) writes `Cancelled` to the Run record; this handler completes the SB message normally.

    Document bytes are NEVER in the payload (ADR-004). If a Tool needs document content, it reads by id from SPE / Dataverse inside the Tool handler. The job message carries IDs only.

    Spec.md FR-16 (manual + scheduled triggers) is the requirement this task addresses for the scheduled half. Manual triggers go through task 040's `/run` endpoint directly.
  </notes>

